## DEEP DX RESEARCH — making the project exceptionally easy to use (2026-06-11)
Analysis of the whole journey from installation to daily development: CLI, Config,
Docs, Workflow, Error Handling, MCP.
**Focus: friction points that make even a "simple" task unpleasant for new users.**

### SETUP & ONBOARDING (DX1-DX4)

**DX1: The Windows WSL requirement is a trap**
- README: "preferably Windows Terminal and WSL (1903+)". This is buried and it is
  not clear that it is REQUIRED.
- 95% of Windows users do not have WSL installed and do not know how to set it up.
- [ ] Add `syncrona check-env` that detects OS, Node, WSL, Git and prints
      actionable next steps.
- [ ] Update README with a visible "⚠️ Windows users" section linking a WSL 2 setup guide.

**DX2: Credential store vs .env confusion**
- The user has 4 sources: env var, CredentialStore, .env, prompt. The fallback
  logic is invisible.
- The wizard does not show the final source — the user does not know where the
  credentials came from.
- Note 2026-06-12: precedence is now unified CLI↔MCP and documented in the mcp
  README (CR17); CLI-side visibility remains.
- [x] DONE 2026-06-13: `syncrona status` now prints "Credentials from: <source>"
      (credential store / instance profile env vars / environment (.env / shell)
      / none). Single internal resolver (resolveCredentialsInternal) reports
      both creds and source so precedence is never duplicated; new
      describeCredentialSource() + credentialSource in StatusSummary; 3 tests
      (credentialSource.test.ts). The test caught a real classification bug
      (base env mis-reported as profile) before it shipped.
- [ ] The wizard should show: "Found SN_INSTANCE in .env. Using this? (yes/no/enter-new)".

**DX3: Multi-instance workflow undocumented**
- `--instance-profile` is in help, but there are no examples; users have to guess
  the syntax.
- No guide for a dev+prod workflow or a safe context switch.
- [ ] Add a `MULTI_INSTANCE.md` guide: profile setup, `syncrona use [instance]`,
      CI/CD examples.

**DX4: Auto-init monorepo is unexpected**
- `syncrona init` with SN_* env vars creates `packages/x_*/` for all scopes.
- The user wonders why they suddenly have 10 new folders.
- [ ] Before auto-init, show: "Found 10 scoped apps. Create packages/x_*/? (y/n)".

---

### CLI INTERFACE (DX5-DX7)

**DX5: Help texts lack examples**
- `syncrona push --help` says "[DESTRUCTIVE]", which is scary, but shows no safe
  workflow examples.
- No `--dry-run` hint in help.
- [x] DONE 2026-06-13: added an `examples` field to the CliCommandModule
      registry (wired through buildCommandBuilder → yargs `.example()`); populated
      examples for dev/push/download/build/status/login/use/mcp, incl.
      `push --dry-run`, `push --diff main`, `push --ci`. Also set
      `.scriptName("syncrona")` so help shows `syncrona <cmd>` not `index.js`.
      e2e smoke test asserts `push --help` carries the examples.

**DX6: The `--diff` flag is unclear**
- `syncrona push --diff main` still pushes everything (it does not filter changed
  files).
- The docs say "audit trail", but the examples are unclear.
- [ ] Add a `--changed-only` flag for a true diff push.
- [ ] Document: `--diff main` = audit (push everything but track changes),
      `--changed-only` = filter.

**DX7: `--instance-profile` on EVERY command is verbose**
- Typical work: `syncrona status --instance-profile dev`,
  `syncrona push --instance-profile dev`.
- The user has to remember the flag every time.
- [ ] Add a `.syncrona-local` config (gitignored): `{ "instanceProfile": "dev" }`.
- [ ] Persist the local profile in `syncrona use [instance]` (not the global store).

---

### CONFIGURATION COMPLEXITY (DX8-DX11)

**DX8: Plugin discovery requires manual names**
- The user must know the "TypeScript plugin" is called "@syncrona/typescript-plugin" on npm.
- `syncrona plugins` shows some but does not help when adding new plugins.
- [ ] Add `syncrona config add-plugin` — an interactive chooser: lists plugins,
      validates, generates boilerplate.

**DX9: Default includes/excludes hidden in code**
- The "sane defaults" live in defaultManifestConfig.ts; users must read source
  code to understand them.
- [ ] `syncrona status` should show "Active includes/excludes" + sources
      (defaults vs overrides).
- [ ] `syncrona config show-defaults` should list all defaults.

**DX10: `sync.config.js` rule order matters, but there is no validation**
- README: "Order your rules by MOST SPECIFIC extension first!" — users can get the
  order wrong and silently fail.
- Note 2026-06-12: a broken config is now a hard fail instead of a silent default
  fallback (CR20), and option names/types are validated (G2); rule-order
  validation remains.
- [ ] `syncrona build --check-config` should validate rule order (`.ts` before `.js`, etc.).
- [ ] `--verbose build` should show which file matched which rule.

**DX11: Advanced options undocumented (`displayField`, `differentiatorField`)**
- TableOptions get one line in the README. When to use them? What is
  `differentiatorField` for?
- "Will break the Windows filesystem" is a bad signal.
- [ ] Document use cases: `displayField` = records with unique names,
      `differentiatorField` = dedup by sys_id.
- [ ] Warning: `differentiatorField` blocks Windows support.

---

### DOCUMENTATION & EXAMPLES (DX12-DX15)

**DX12: The FAQ is thin**
- There is "How do I Delete Something?" and "How do I Add Scripts?", but nothing on
  "How do I work with multiple instances?" or error recovery.
- [ ] Add FAQ: multi-user workflow, environment switching, performance tuning,
      troubleshooting.
- [ ] A "Getting Unstuck" section: common problems + solutions.

**DX13: Plugin development docs are missing**
- A user writing a plugin reads source code. No spec, lifecycle, API.
- [ ] `PLUGIN_DEVELOPMENT.md`: template plugin, example transformations, interface spec.

**DX14: Workspace/monorepo guide is missing**
- README: "run from specific scope directory", but no full workflow example
  (init, configure, share deps, CI/CD).
- [ ] `docs/MONOREPO_GUIDE.md`: structure, per-scope config, shared node_modules,
      pipeline examples.

**DX15: MCP integration docs have hardcoded paths and are thin**
- The MCP quickstart contains `/Users/Ivan.Baev/Development/...` in examples.
- No explanation of what auto-pull is, why, and when to disable it.
- [ ] Update with $HOME substitution or a template generator.
- [ ] Document auto-pull and MCP startup troubleshooting.

---

### WORKFLOW & DEVELOPER EXPERIENCE (DX16-DX18)

**DX16: Manifest refresh interval is hidden config**
- `refreshInterval: 30` is the default. A user on a slow network suffers.
- No clear documentation of what the 30-second refresh does.
- Note 2026-06-12: overlapping interval refreshes are now guarded (CR11).
- [ ] Document refresh behavior and performance.
- [x] `--verbose dev` should print "Manifest refresh took Xms" — DONE 2026-06-13:
      the refresher logs `Manifest refresh took Xms` at debug level (DX21).
- [x] A `syncrona dev --refresh-interval 60` flag — DONE 2026-06-13:
      `dev --refresh-interval N` (alias --refreshInterval) overrides
      sync.config.js refreshInterval; 0 disables polling.

**DX17: The file structure is strange for new users**
- "Records are shown as folders…", but users expect a flat structure
  (src/scripts/my.js).
- [ ] Add a `--flat` mode: flat locally, converted automatically before push/pull.

**DX18: Error recovery is undocumented**
- Partial push failure (network dies). The user does not know whether a retry is safe.
- Note 2026-06-12: checkpoint/resume no longer leaves bogus state after a declined
  prompt (CR5); the lock is released even on errors (CR6); behavior is documented
  in the core README ("Push recovery and locking").
- [ ] `syncrona repair` should compare manifest vs actual files and repair.

---

### ERROR MESSAGES & DEBUGGING (DX19-DX21)

**DX19: Generic error messages do not help**
- Good example: "Your scope is X but config is Y". Many other errors: "Error
  processing response".
- Note 2026-06-12: scopeCheck now shows the real error instead of the generic
  "Failed to check your scope" (CR9); buildCommand now logs the failure (CR8).
- [ ] Error categorization: "Network" (retry), "Config" (fix), "Data" (support).
- [ ] Actionable next steps for every error.

**DX20: Silent error swallowing during credential loading**
- As AR10 noted, secrets-loading errors are swallowed. Users do not know whether
  their .env is invalid.
- [x] DONE 2026-06-13: `syncrona status --debug-credentials` prints every source —
      base env presence, profile env presence, credential-store instances + active,
      and the resolved winner. Backed by snClient.diagnoseCredentials (reuses the
      resolver's profile naming, no drift). 3 unit tests.
      It immediately earned its keep: on this machine it revealed that the active
      stored instance (ven03019) FAILS to decrypt ("unable to authenticate data"),
      which is why plain `status` reported "credentials missing". The debug view
      now reports the decrypt failure + hint ("re-run syncrona login"); previously
      resolveCredentialsFromStore swallowed it silently.
- [x] **DX20b** — DONE 2026-06-13: plain `syncrona status` (not just
      --debug-credentials) now appends an error when the active stored instance
      fails to decrypt: "Stored credentials for X failed to decrypt (…) — re-run
      'syncrona login'." Shared activeStoreHealth() helper backs both the normal
      and debug paths (decrypt check defined once). Verified live (the ven03019
      fixture surfaces the warning). commandsFlow status tests made hermetic by
      mocking ../auth.
      Residual: push/download with stored-only creds still fail with a raw auth
      error rather than this hint — generalizing the warning to those paths
      (or un-swallowing in resolveCredentialsFromStore) is a larger follow-up.

**DX21: Verbose logging is incomplete**
- `--log-level debug` exists but the output is silent. A stuck user cannot see
  what is happening.
- [ ] Profiled log points: "Starting refresh…", "Queued 5 files…", "Waiting for API…".

---

### ADVANCED FEATURES (DX22-DX24)

**DX22: Dry-run output is JSON instead of a table**
- The user cannot easily see which files would be pushed.
- [ ] Table format: `File | Action | Changes | Size`.

**DX23: The `--diff` feature is under-documented**
- Users do not know it exists for audit trail / compliance review.
- [ ] Document the use case clearly.

**DX24: Rate limiting & concurrency are invisible**
- `pushConcurrency: 10` is configurable via sync.config.js but has no CLI flag.
  No progress bar for long pushes.
- [x] A `--push-concurrency N` flag — DONE 2026-06-13: `push --concurrency N`
      (aliases --push-concurrency / --pushConcurrency) overrides sync.config.js
      pushConcurrency, clamped 1-50, falls back to 10. resolvePushConcurrency
      takes an optional override; pushFiles threads args.pushConcurrency (deploy
      and watch keep the config default). 4 unit tests + help example.
- [ ] Progress bar: "Pushing [███░] 30/100 (2m remaining)". (push already has a
      progress tick via getProgTick; a richer ETA bar remains.)

